01:45.171 --> 01:47.673
Detective Donohue,
how good of you to come.

01:47.674 --> 01:49.174
I came by to say one thing.

01:49.175 --> 01:50.676
I'd like very much to see you,

01:50.677 --> 01:52.177
so when you feel
the time is proper,

01:52.178 --> 01:53.178
will you let me know?

01:53.179 --> 01:55.180
The time is proper now,
detective.

01:55.181 --> 01:56.181
It is?
Mm-hmm.

01:56.182 --> 01:59.184
Yes, because
you make me feel good,

01:59.185 --> 02:01.186
and whenever
you make a person feel good,

02:01.187 --> 02:03.188
the time is always proper.

02:03.189 --> 02:05.190
Okay.
Good.

02:05.191 --> 02:07.693
Uh, excuse me, everyone.

02:07.694 --> 02:09.695
Uh, this is Detective Donohue...

02:09.696 --> 02:11.697
you know, who
looked for Chester.

02:11.698 --> 02:13.198
How do you do?

02:13.199 --> 02:15.701
May I have your attention,
please?

02:15.702 --> 02:17.202
I want to thank you,
first of all,

02:17.203 --> 02:18.704
for coming here today.

02:18.705 --> 02:19.705
As you know,

02:19.706 --> 02:22.207
Chester never cared
for funerals...

02:22.208 --> 02:24.209
Especially his own.

02:24.210 --> 02:27.212
And in his will,
as a tribute to his memory,

02:27.213 --> 02:30.215
he asked that all of his family
and all of his friends

02:30.216 --> 02:31.216
get together

02:31.217 --> 02:33.719
and just tell
all those wild, funny stories

02:33.720 --> 02:35.220
about him.

02:35.221 --> 02:38.223
And I did invite, uh,

02:38.224 --> 02:40.225
oh, about 40
of his closest friends.

02:40.226 --> 02:43.729
They all had headaches,

02:43.730 --> 02:45.731
so come on, everybody,

02:45.732 --> 02:47.232
let's just toss out

02:47.233 --> 02:48.734
all of those funny stories

02:48.735 --> 02:50.235
about Chester.

02:50.236 --> 02:53.739
Who would like to go first?

03:00.246 --> 03:01.747
Oh, well, I've got one.

03:01.748 --> 03:03.749
Uh... Uh...

03:03.750 --> 03:06.251
One morning,
Chester came down to breakfast

03:06.252 --> 03:09.254
with shaving cream
still behind his ear.

03:09.255 --> 03:11.257
[GIGGLES]

03:13.259 --> 03:15.761
I said to him...

03:15.762 --> 03:19.265
"Chester, you forgot to..."

03:24.771 --> 03:27.272
"You forgot
to wipe off the cream."

03:27.273 --> 03:30.275
He forgot to wipe off...

03:30.276 --> 03:31.777
[LAUGHING CONTINUES]

03:36.783 --> 03:39.284
So...

03:39.285 --> 03:40.786
Chester went
all the way back upstairs,

03:40.787 --> 03:43.289
and I...

03:44.290 --> 03:47.292
I poured him
some o-orange juice.

03:47.293 --> 03:49.795
Orange juice!
A-ha-ha-haa!

03:53.299 --> 03:54.800
And then he said...

03:57.303 --> 04:01.807
And then he said,
"Is it all off now?"

04:01.808 --> 04:05.310
And I said...

04:05.311 --> 04:08.313
I said, "Yes.

04:08.314 --> 04:10.816
How do you want your eggs?"

04:15.321 --> 04:16.321
Eggs.

04:16.322 --> 04:19.324
Oh, yeah. I get it!

04:19.325 --> 04:21.327
[HIGH-PITCHED LAUGHTER]

04:26.833 --> 04:28.333
Oh, golly.

04:28.334 --> 04:29.835
Oh, this is fun.

04:32.839 --> 04:35.341
Who would like to be next?

04:38.344 --> 04:40.846
Billy, why don't you tell
the hammer story?

04:40.847 --> 04:42.848
No, Ma, I don't think so.

04:42.849 --> 04:44.349
Oh, come on, honey.

04:44.350 --> 04:45.350
Good idea.
Do it.

04:45.351 --> 04:46.351
That would be terrific.

04:46.352 --> 04:48.353
Do it, do it.
Please. Come on.

04:48.354 --> 04:49.855
It's cute. It's cute.

04:49.856 --> 04:51.356
All right.

04:51.357 --> 04:53.859
Well, when I was five,
I asked Dad to buy me a hammer.

04:53.860 --> 04:55.360
He asked me
what I wanted it for,

04:55.361 --> 04:57.362
and I told him
I wanted to build a puppy.

04:57.363 --> 04:58.864
All the other kids had puppies,

04:58.865 --> 05:02.367
and I wanted one so badly
that I decided to build one.

05:02.368 --> 05:03.368
Did he buy you the puppy?

05:03.369 --> 05:05.371
No, he bought me the hammer.

05:07.373 --> 05:08.874
Your father

05:08.875 --> 05:10.877
was an incredible human being.

05:15.882 --> 05:17.382
Corinne?

05:17.383 --> 05:19.885
Uh...

05:19.886 --> 05:21.887
Okay.

05:21.888 --> 05:23.889
Um...

05:23.890 --> 05:26.892
when I was little,

05:26.893 --> 05:28.393
Daddy took me fishing,

05:28.394 --> 05:31.396
and I remember that day
he caught a lot of fish,

05:31.397 --> 05:32.898
and I didn't catch anything,

05:32.899 --> 05:35.901
and I remember
feeling a little sad

05:35.902 --> 05:38.403
and very puzzled
when Daddy announced

05:38.404 --> 05:39.905
that he was going swimming,

05:39.906 --> 05:41.406
and he jumped overboard

05:41.407 --> 05:44.409
with one of the fish
in his belt.

05:44.410 --> 05:45.410
Well,

05:45.411 --> 05:46.912
a few minutes later,

05:46.913 --> 05:50.415
Daddy came up
without the fish, and...

05:50.416 --> 05:53.418
and I felt a little tug
on my line,

05:53.419 --> 05:55.420
and I reeled it in,

05:55.421 --> 05:58.924
and there was the fish.

05:58.925 --> 06:01.927
What a wonderful story.

06:01.928 --> 06:02.928
What a guy.

06:02.929 --> 06:04.931
What a crock.

06:06.893 --> 06:07.933
He never took you fishing.

06:07.934 --> 06:09.434
Shh.

06:09.435 --> 06:10.936
She's real good
at making up stories,

06:10.937 --> 06:11.937
isn't she?

06:11.938 --> 06:13.939
Tim, it's your baby.

06:13.940 --> 06:15.941
Benson, you believe me,

06:15.942 --> 06:17.443
don't you?

06:20.446 --> 06:22.948
Uh, Jodie? Jodie?

06:22.949 --> 06:23.950
There he is.

06:26.452 --> 06:27.452
Come on, Jodie,

06:27.453 --> 06:28.453
don't you have a story

06:28.454 --> 06:29.454
you want to share with us?

06:29.455 --> 06:33.959
I just love the way
Jodie tells a story.

06:33.960 --> 06:34.960
Well, all right.

06:34.961 --> 06:35.961
Well, uh...

06:35.962 --> 06:37.462
once, I remember,

06:37.463 --> 06:40.966
I asked Uncle Chester why
he always wore black shoes...

06:40.967 --> 06:43.468
and, uh...

06:43.469 --> 06:44.970
he said, "I don't know.

06:44.971 --> 06:46.973
I just find then comfortable."

06:54.480 --> 06:57.983
A story like that
comes around once, maybe twice.

06:57.984 --> 06:58.985
Not often.

07:00.486 --> 07:01.486
Burt?

07:01.487 --> 07:02.487
There he is.

07:02.488 --> 07:03.989
Oh, yeah.

07:03.990 --> 07:05.490
No, I...

07:05.491 --> 07:06.992
I remember Chester.

07:09.996 --> 07:11.997
I was, um...

07:11.998 --> 07:12.998
I remember there was...

07:12.999 --> 07:13.999
Oh.

07:14.000 --> 07:16.501
[LAUGHS]

07:16.502 --> 07:19.505
I remember one time he came,
and...

07:22.008 --> 07:24.509
That wasn't him.

07:24.510 --> 07:26.011
I remember,
and then I don't sometimes,

07:26.012 --> 07:28.514
but it's like...
Next?

07:31.017 --> 07:33.018
Aunt Jessie, I've got one.

07:33.019 --> 07:35.020
Oh. Good.

07:35.021 --> 07:36.021
This is really funny.

07:36.022 --> 07:38.023
I remember once, uh...

07:38.024 --> 07:40.025
Burt had some dough
he wanted to invest,

07:40.026 --> 07:44.029
and Chester suggested
rotary engine fan belts.

07:44.030 --> 07:45.030
Uh, Danny, that's not funny.

07:45.031 --> 07:46.031
Come on.

07:46.032 --> 07:47.532
Aw, come on, it's really good.

07:47.533 --> 07:48.533
So anyway,

07:48.534 --> 07:51.036
Burt gives him the dough,
and Chester invests it,

07:51.037 --> 07:54.039
and the next day,
the company went broke.

07:54.040 --> 07:56.041
Burt was cleaned out.

07:56.042 --> 07:57.042
[ALL LAUGHING]

07:57.043 --> 07:58.543
Very funny.

07:58.544 --> 08:01.547
What are you doing?

08:04.050 --> 08:05.550
Daddy.

08:05.551 --> 08:07.052
Aye.

08:07.053 --> 08:09.554
This was a brave man.

08:09.555 --> 08:11.556
This was a courageous man.

08:11.557 --> 08:16.061
This was a man who always
did more than his duty.

08:16.062 --> 08:19.064
He was right there
to the very end.

08:19.065 --> 08:21.566
Never was there another man
like him.

08:21.567 --> 08:24.569
Never will there be
another man like him.

08:24.570 --> 08:26.071
He was one of a kind.

08:26.072 --> 08:28.073
We shall never forget him.

08:28.074 --> 08:30.575
He was a leader of men.

08:30.576 --> 08:34.078
We have lost the best.

08:34.080 --> 08:40.586
His family, his friend...

08:43.589 --> 08:49.594
And the United States of America
will never forget

08:49.595 --> 08:54.099
General Mike
"Smilin' Bob" Hawkins.

08:54.100 --> 08:57.102
Daddy... Daddy.

08:57.103 --> 08:58.603
General Hawkins didn't die.

08:58.604 --> 09:00.105
Chester died.

09:00.106 --> 09:02.608
Oh. Good.

09:05.111 --> 09:07.613
Never mind. As you were.

09:10.616 --> 09:11.617
Mary?

09:14.620 --> 09:16.121
Well, I would just like to say

09:16.122 --> 09:17.622
that I think

09:17.623 --> 09:22.127
that all our lives are richer
for having known him.

09:22.128 --> 09:24.129
Benson, do you have
any fond memories

09:24.130 --> 09:25.130
of Mr. Tate

09:25.131 --> 09:26.632
you'd like to share with us?

09:29.635 --> 09:31.636
No.

09:31.637 --> 09:37.642
Uh, and, uh...
I believe that, uh...

09:37.643 --> 09:39.644
he will be remembered fondly

09:39.645 --> 09:41.646
by those of us who loved him.

09:41.647 --> 09:44.650
And the rest of us too.

09:50.156 --> 09:51.657
[DOORBELL RINGS]

09:58.164 --> 09:59.164
Mrs. Campbell?

09:59.165 --> 10:00.165
Yes?

10:00.166 --> 10:01.166
Hi. I'm Sally.

10:01.167 --> 10:02.167
Sally?

10:02.168 --> 10:03.668
Your husband's secretary.

10:03.669 --> 10:06.671
Oh, Sally.

10:06.672 --> 10:07.672
Come in.

10:07.673 --> 10:08.673
Thank you.
Thank you.

10:08.674 --> 10:10.175
Well, I'm...

10:10.176 --> 10:11.176
I'm pleased to meet you.

10:11.177 --> 10:14.179
You've always been
just a voice on the telephone.

10:14.180 --> 10:15.180
Uh, sit down.

10:15.181 --> 10:16.181
Thanks.

10:18.184 --> 10:20.185
Uh...

10:20.186 --> 10:21.186
Mrs. Campbell,
I don't really...

10:21.187 --> 10:22.687
Mary. Mary.

10:22.688 --> 10:24.689
Mary.

10:24.690 --> 10:26.691
Mary, I don't know how to...

10:26.692 --> 10:27.692
put this.

10:27.693 --> 10:28.693
What?

10:28.694 --> 10:32.697
Well, your husband and I

10:32.698 --> 10:33.779
have been having an affair.

10:35.201 --> 10:36.701
So what happened was,
the other day,

10:36.702 --> 10:37.702
he came by...

10:37.703 --> 10:39.204
Wait a second.
Wait a second.

10:39.205 --> 10:40.705
Could you just back up a little?

10:40.706 --> 10:41.706
Sure.

10:41.707 --> 10:44.209
Did you say you and Burt...

10:44.210 --> 10:45.710
Right.

10:45.711 --> 10:46.711
So what happened was,
the other day...

10:46.712 --> 10:48.213
You and Burt?

10:48.214 --> 10:51.216
Me and Burt.

10:51.217 --> 10:52.717
Well, Burt and I.

10:52.718 --> 10:53.718
It's Burt and I.

10:53.719 --> 10:55.220
I always get those confused...

10:55.221 --> 10:57.222
me and him, he and I, he and me.

10:57.223 --> 10:58.224
I hated grammar.

11:01.227 --> 11:02.727
You don't, uh...

11:02.728 --> 11:04.229
you don't look like
what I imagined.

11:04.230 --> 11:05.730
You imagined someone?

11:05.731 --> 11:07.732
Well, Burt told me
that he spent the night

11:07.733 --> 11:08.733
with someone once,

11:08.734 --> 11:10.235
and that she was fat and old.

11:13.239 --> 11:16.241
Were you once fat?

11:16.242 --> 11:17.742
Or old?

11:17.743 --> 11:20.745
It must have been someone else.

11:20.746 --> 11:22.747
Mrs. Campbell...

11:22.748 --> 11:23.748
Mary...
I really just...

11:23.749 --> 11:25.250
Mrs. Campbell.

11:28.754 --> 11:31.256
Look, don't be mad at me.

11:31.257 --> 11:33.758
I felt sorry for him.

11:33.759 --> 11:34.759
I have never had an affair

11:34.760 --> 11:35.760
with a married man.

11:35.761 --> 11:38.263
I would not do that.

11:38.264 --> 11:42.767
But he told me he was miserable.

11:42.768 --> 11:45.770
He said you were a mean, hard...

11:45.771 --> 11:47.272
bitter lady.

11:49.275 --> 11:54.279
And I believed him. And then...

11:54.280 --> 11:57.282
Then I fell in love with him.

11:57.283 --> 11:59.285
So please, don't be mad at me.

12:02.288 --> 12:04.789
I can't believe it.

12:04.790 --> 12:06.291
I can't believe it.

12:06.292 --> 12:07.792
I don't believe...

12:07.793 --> 12:09.294
you and him.

12:09.295 --> 12:10.795
I think it's
"you and he."

12:10.796 --> 12:12.297
See, it would be "him and me",

12:12.298 --> 12:13.798
so I think
it's "you and he."

12:13.799 --> 12:15.800
Don't get me wrong.

12:15.801 --> 12:20.305
I'm not saying I don't believe
he'd have an affair with you.

12:20.306 --> 12:21.806
What I'm saying is

12:21.807 --> 12:25.310
that I find it hard to accept
he's having an affair.

12:25.311 --> 12:26.811
But if he was having an affair,

12:26.812 --> 12:29.314
I'm sure
that the affair he was having

12:29.315 --> 12:30.315
would be with you.

12:33.819 --> 12:35.320
You're very, uh...
pretty.

12:35.321 --> 12:36.821
Oh. Thank you.

12:36.822 --> 12:38.323
Young.

12:39.825 --> 12:40.826
Skinny.

12:43.329 --> 12:44.329
I'm not skinny.

12:44.330 --> 12:46.831
Please, you're skinny.

12:46.832 --> 12:49.834
I'm five pounds overweight.

12:49.835 --> 12:51.336
Oh, please. You are not.

12:51.337 --> 12:54.339
I am. I mean, I starve myself.
I still can't lose.

12:54.340 --> 12:56.342
I know. It's so depressing.

12:58.344 --> 12:59.844
You know the Atkins diet?

12:59.845 --> 13:02.847
Do I know it?
I've been on it 12 times.

13:02.848 --> 13:04.349
I gained.

13:04.350 --> 13:05.350
Metabolism.

13:05.351 --> 13:06.851
Fasting? Gained.

13:06.852 --> 13:07.852
You and Burt.

13:07.853 --> 13:09.354
You know,

13:09.355 --> 13:10.855
you're taking this very well.

13:10.856 --> 13:12.357
No, I'm not.

13:12.358 --> 13:13.858
Yes, you are.

13:13.859 --> 13:16.361
You're taking this beautifully.

13:16.362 --> 13:20.365
No. I'm in shock.
That's what it is.

13:20.366 --> 13:21.866
I'm not taking it with grace.

13:21.867 --> 13:23.368
I'm taking it with shock.

13:26.372 --> 13:28.373
There's more.

13:28.374 --> 13:30.376
Oh, good.
Maybe this'll kill me.

13:32.378 --> 13:36.381
The other day
I discovered that...

13:36.382 --> 13:37.383
Are you ready?

13:40.386 --> 13:42.887
Burt's been cheating on me.

13:42.888 --> 13:45.890
When did he have the time?

13:45.891 --> 13:48.393
I know.
It's incredible, isn't it?

13:48.394 --> 13:49.394
Her, me, you.

13:49.395 --> 13:50.395
It's a wonder he isn't dead.

13:50.396 --> 13:52.397
He will be.
I'm gonna kill him.

13:52.398 --> 13:55.900
No. I am.

13:55.901 --> 13:57.402
Wait till you hear this.

13:57.403 --> 13:58.403
She's 18.

13:58.404 --> 14:00.405
18?

14:00.406 --> 14:01.406
18.

14:01.407 --> 14:04.409
Skinny?

14:04.410 --> 14:06.912
She's 18. Who cares?

14:09.415 --> 14:12.417
18.

14:12.418 --> 14:14.919
What do they talk about at 18?

14:14.920 --> 14:17.922
What she did in school today?

14:17.923 --> 14:20.425
It's disgusting.

14:20.426 --> 14:21.927
18.

14:24.930 --> 14:25.930
I am so sorry

14:25.931 --> 14:28.433
I had to tell you all this.

14:28.434 --> 14:30.435
Oh. No. Thank you.

14:30.436 --> 14:32.437
[SIGHS]

14:32.438 --> 14:34.939
I'm glad you did.

14:34.940 --> 14:36.941
Where are my manners?

14:36.942 --> 14:37.942
Would you like a drink?

14:37.943 --> 14:39.444
Oh, please,
Mrs. Campbell.

14:39.445 --> 14:40.446
Call me Mary.

14:49.955 --> 14:50.955
[DOORBELL RINGS]

14:58.464 --> 14:59.964
Hi. Uh, Mrs. David?

14:59.965 --> 15:01.967
Yes?

15:03.969 --> 15:04.969
I'm Jodie.

15:04.970 --> 15:09.974
Oh, my.
Oh, my, my, my.

15:09.975 --> 15:10.975
You're in Texas.

15:10.976 --> 15:13.979
I think so.
Everybody talks funny.

15:15.481 --> 15:18.983
Well, come on in...
for a minute.

15:18.984 --> 15:19.985
Thank you.

15:22.988 --> 15:24.489
You're a homo?

15:35.000 --> 15:36.000
Well, I, uh...

15:36.001 --> 15:39.004
The reason I ask is
I never seen one before.

15:41.006 --> 15:44.009
We don't have homos in Texas.

15:45.511 --> 15:48.514
Live ones, anyway.

15:51.016 --> 15:53.518
Well, sit down.

15:53.519 --> 15:54.519
Would you like a drink?

15:54.520 --> 15:57.021
Uh, yes, thank you.
A drink would be nice.

15:57.022 --> 15:59.524
What do you people drink?

15:59.525 --> 16:01.526
You mean New Yorkers?
We drink...

16:01.527 --> 16:04.028
No, no, homos.

16:04.029 --> 16:08.032
We drink
your basic heterosexual drinks.

16:08.033 --> 16:11.536
How about some lemonade?
Do you drink lemonade?

16:11.537 --> 16:14.038
Lemonade would be terrific.
We like lemonade.

16:14.039 --> 16:17.041
I mean,
we drink a lot of lemonade.

16:17.042 --> 16:20.545
Uh, Mrs. David,
is Carol around?

16:20.546 --> 16:22.547
Upstairs.

16:22.548 --> 16:24.549
But I don't think
she wants to see you.

16:24.550 --> 16:28.052
Mrs. David, I've flown
clear across the country.

16:28.053 --> 16:29.554
This is a very big state.

16:29.555 --> 16:32.057
It took me a day and a half
to drive here from the airport.

16:33.058 --> 16:34.059
Yeah.

16:35.561 --> 16:37.562
Uh, uh...

16:37.563 --> 16:39.063
I've gone through a lot
to get here,

16:39.064 --> 16:41.065
and I intend to see Carol.

16:41.066 --> 16:43.568
Okay.

16:43.569 --> 16:44.569
[SHOUTS] Carol!

16:44.570 --> 16:46.571
Carol, honey,
you've got a visitor!

16:46.572 --> 16:49.575
Oh... this'll put a run
in her pantyhose.

16:54.580 --> 16:55.580
Jodie.

16:55.581 --> 16:57.081
Hi.

16:57.082 --> 16:59.083
I didn't... I...

16:59.084 --> 17:01.085
I thought it would be nice
to surprise you.

17:01.086 --> 17:03.588
Oh, yes. Nice.

17:03.589 --> 17:06.089
He sure surprised me.

17:06.090 --> 17:09.594
He looks perfectly normal.

17:09.595 --> 17:10.595
Mother.

17:10.596 --> 17:13.097
I guess I expected him
to wear organdy.

17:13.098 --> 17:14.098
Mother...

17:14.098 --> 17:16.099
Hmm?
Do you mind?

17:16.101 --> 17:18.102
Oh.

17:18.103 --> 17:20.104
It was nice meeting you, Jodie.

17:20.105 --> 17:21.606
Nice meeting you,
Mrs. David.

17:21.607 --> 17:23.608
You're my first homo.

17:23.608 --> 17:25.609
[IMITATES MRS. DAVID'S VOICE]
You're my first Texan.

17:25.611 --> 17:27.612
[GASPS] Ah!

17:27.613 --> 17:28.613
Yeah.

17:32.618 --> 17:34.119
This is a... surprise.

17:36.622 --> 17:38.624
Jodie, I'm so sorry.

17:40.626 --> 17:43.127
I felt awful.

17:43.128 --> 17:45.130
You have no idea
how awful I felt.

17:46.632 --> 17:50.635
Uh, what it was... was, uh...

17:50.636 --> 17:53.638
Carol, I know what it was.

17:53.639 --> 17:56.140
I mean, suddenly it didn't seem
like such a terrific idea

17:56.141 --> 17:57.642
to have a husband
who is a homosexual.

17:57.643 --> 18:00.645
It was just that
I thought that you...

18:00.646 --> 18:02.648
What about the baby?

18:04.650 --> 18:06.150
What about the baby?

18:06.151 --> 18:07.151
Well, I'd, uh...

18:07.152 --> 18:10.154
I'd like to see
my child grow up.

18:10.155 --> 18:14.158
Jodie, I don't want you
to be the baby's father.

18:14.159 --> 18:16.160
Carol, I don't think
you have that choice anymore.

18:16.161 --> 18:19.163
I don't want you
to see the baby.

18:19.164 --> 18:20.164
What?

18:20.165 --> 18:23.668
Someday I hope to marry,

18:23.669 --> 18:26.170
and whoever I marry
will be the baby's father.

18:26.171 --> 18:28.673
Carol, that's my baby.
You can't do this.

18:30.175 --> 18:33.678
Carol, please.

18:33.679 --> 18:34.679
What am I gonna do?

18:34.680 --> 18:39.183
I don't stand a chance in court.

18:39.184 --> 18:44.188
I have feelings, Carol.
It's my baby, and I care.

18:44.189 --> 18:47.191
I don't think
I've ever cared about anything

18:47.192 --> 18:48.192
quite as much.

18:48.193 --> 18:53.197
Jodie, I know I'm right.

18:53.198 --> 18:54.198
Now, I know it's hard for you,

18:54.199 --> 18:57.201
but I know I'm doing
the right thing.

18:57.202 --> 19:01.205
You mean my child
will never know I'm his father?

19:01.206 --> 19:03.708
It's better this way.

19:03.709 --> 19:05.710
Carol, it's a mistake.

19:05.711 --> 19:09.213
It's a gigantic mistake
because it's a lie,

19:09.214 --> 19:11.015
and a lie will always
catch up with you later.

19:13.719 --> 19:17.221
And when it does, Carol...

19:17.222 --> 19:21.225
When my child wants his father,

19:21.226 --> 19:22.227
I'll be there.

